{{about|the feature in plant morphology}}
'''''Calyptra''''' (from [[wikt:καλύπτρα#Ancient Greek|καλύπτρα]] (''kalúptra'') "veil") is a scientific term used in [[botany]]. It describes a feature in [[plant morphology]]. [[Image:Tortula muralis kalyptra.jpeg|thumb|300px|Calyptra of tortula moss ''Tortula muralis'']] [[Image:Physcomitrella Sporophyt.JPG|thumb|300px|Calyptra on top of the brown spore capsule (sporophyte) of the moss ''[[Physcomitrella patens]]''. The brownish archegonial venter is still visible.]]
==Bryophytes== In [[bryophytes]], the '''calyptra''' (''plural'' calyptrae) is an enlarged [[Archegonium|archegonial]] venter that protects the capsule containing the embryonic [[sporophyte]].<ref>[[Ralf Reski]] (1998): Development, genetics and molecular biology of mosses. In: Botanica Acta. 111, 1-15.</ref> The calyptra is usually lost before the spores are released from the capsule. The shape of the calyptra can be used for identification purposes.<ref>{{Citation| last=Malcolm; Malcolm| first= Bill; Nancy| title= Mosses and other Bryophytes, an Illustrated Glossary| year=2006| publisher=Micro-Optics Press| page=65| isbn=0-9582224-7-9}}</ref>
==Flowering plants== In [[flowering plant]]s, the calyptra is a covering tissue for [[stamen]]s and [[carpel]]s. The name is also used for the capping tissue of [[root]]s, the [[root cap]].
