The '''Fiber-Optic Improved Next-Generation Doppler Search for Exo-Earths''' ('''FINDS Exo-Earths''') is a [[radial velocity method|radial-velocity]] [[spectrograph]] developed by [[Debra Fischer]]. It is installed on the 3 m telescope in [[Lick Observatory]] in [[Mount Hamilton (California)|Mount Hamilton]]. It has been in operation since 2009 and is being used to verify exoplanet candidates found by [[Kepler (spacecraft)|Kepler]].
At Yale University, Debra Fischer and Julien Spronck, along with Geoff Marcy of the University of California, Berkeley, set out to improve existing spectrograph technologies. Spurred by a $45,000 grant from [[The Planetary Society]], the team built FINDS, a spectrograph add-on device.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.planetary.org/explore/projects/exoplanets/finds.html |title=FINDS Exo-Earths |work=The Planetary Society |date=2009 |accessdate=2015-05-31 }}</ref>
==See also==
* [[Anglo-Australian Planet Search]] or ''AAPS'' is another southern hemisphere planet search program. * [[CORALIE spectrograph]] is a similar instrument. * [[ELODIE spectrograph]] is the precursor instrument. * [[ESPRESSO]] is a new-generation spectrograph for [[ESO]]'s [[Very Large Telescope|VLT]]. * [[HARPS]] is a similar instrument in La Silla. * [[List of extrasolar planets]] * [[SOPHIE échelle spectrograph]] is a similar instrument.
